node.title: NSW records nine Omicron COVID cases as Newcastle nightclub cluster explodes
node.alt: the outside courtyard of a night club
node.description: NSW Health says the state recorded nine new Omicron COVID-19 cases, bringing the total numberÂ to 64.
node.content:
["NSW has recorded nine new Omicron COVID-19 cases, bringing the total number in the state to 64.", "Public health authorities have also issued a warning about the Argyle House nightclub in Newcastle after 60 more COVID-19 cases were recorded overnight, bringing the cluster size\u00a0to 84.", "NSW Health said \"a number of these cases are likely to be the Omicron variant\".", "Any person who attended the nightclub between 9pm on Wednesday, December 8 and 3am on Thursday, December 9 is considered a close contact.", "Three of the nightclub patrons are linked to a party boat cruise on Sydney Harbour two week ago, that has been the source of a number Omicron infections.", "The Hunter New England Health District yesterday recorded its first Omicron case, from a recently returned traveller from the UK.", "She's not connected to the Argyle COVID cluster, and Hunter Public Health Controller David Durrheim said the woman was isolating at home.", "NSW Premier Dominic Perrottet said last week the emergence of Omicron and current COVID-19 cases were unlikely to impact the raft of restrictions being eased on Wednesday.", "The latest outbreak comes as the state\u00a0recorded 536 new infections and zero deaths in the 24 hours to 8pm last night.", "There are currently 171 COVID-19 cases admitted to hospital, with 24 people in intensive care, nine of whom require ventilation.", "There were 74,997 COVID-19 tests reported to 8pm last night, compared with the previous day's total of 90,804.", "Across NSW, 94.8 per cent of people aged 16 and over have received a first dose of a COVID-19 vaccine, and 93.1 per cent are fully vaccinated.", "Of the people aged 12 to 15, 81.4 per cent have received a first dose of COVID-19 vaccine, and 77.7 per cent are fully vaccinated.", "More to come.", "", "
Why we hear about some COVID-19 variants more than others
"]
